Lin-Manuel Miranda (born January 16, 1980) is an American songwriter, actor, filmmaker, and librettist. His creative output has fundamentally reshaped contemporary musical theatre, most notably through his groundbreaking Broadway productions [In the Heights](/In_the_Heights) and [Hamilton](/Hamilton_(musical)). Beyond the stage, he has lent his distinctive musical talents to a variety of projects, including the soundtracks for Disney's animated features [Moana](/Moana_(2016_film)), [Vivo](/Vivo_(film)), and [Encanto](/Encanto). Miranda's prolific career has been recognized with a multitude of prestigious awards, including a [Pulitzer Prize for Drama](/Pulitzer_Prize_for_Drama), three [Tony Awards](/Tony_Awards), two [Laurence Olivier Awards](/Laurence_Olivier_Awards), two [Emmy Awards](/Emmy_Awards), and five [Grammy Awards](/Grammy_Awards). He has also garnered nominations for two [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards) and was honored with a [Kennedy Center Honor](/Kennedy_Center_Honors) in 2018.

### Early Life and Education

Born in [New York City](/New_York_City) on January 16, 1980, Lin-Manuel Miranda is the son of Luz Towns-Miranda, a clinical psychologist, and [Luis Miranda Jr.](/Luis_A._Miranda_Jr.), a prominent [political consultant](/Political_consultant). His heritage is predominantly [Puerto Rican](/Puerto_Ricans), with threads of Mexican, English, and African American ancestry woven into his family history. The name "Lin-Manuel" itself carries a literary significance, inspired by a poem about the [Vietnam War](/Vietnam_War) by Puerto Rican writer José Manuel Torres Santiago. He spent his formative years in the [Inwood](/Inwood,_Manhattan) neighborhood of [Manhattan](/Manhattan), raised within the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church). A significant part of his childhood involved spending at least a month each year with his grandparents in [Vega Alta, Puerto Rico](/Vega_Alta,_Puerto_Rico), fostering a deep connection to his cultural roots. He has an older sister, Luz, who has carved out a successful career in strategic consulting.

Miranda's academic journey led him through [Hunter College Elementary School](/Hunter_College_Elementary_School) and [Hunter College High School](/Hunter_College_High_School). It was during his time at Hunter College High School that he first encountered the world of theatre, with journalist [Chris Hayes](/Chris_Hayes) directing him in a student production. This early theatrical experience, albeit a "maniacal fetal pig in a nightmare," sparked a creative fire. He also crossed paths with rapper [Immortal Technique](/Immortal_Technique), who, despite a history of bullying, later became an acquaintance. It was during his school years that Miranda began to seriously explore writing musicals, laying the groundwork for his future endeavors.

In 1999, during his sophomore year at [Wesleyan University](/Wesleyan_University), Miranda began drafting what would eventually become *[In the Heights](/In_the_Heights)*. The university's student theater company, Second Stage, embraced his work, leading to its premiere that same year. Miranda further enriched the production by incorporating freestyle rap and salsa numbers, showcasing his burgeoning musical style. Throughout his time at Wesleyan, he not only wrote and directed several other musicals but also actively participated in a wide array of theatrical productions, from musicals to [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare) plays. He graduated from Wesleyan in 2002, armed with a [Bachelor of Arts](/Bachelor_of_Arts) degree and a clear vision for his artistic future.

### Career

#### Theatre

**2002–2011: *In the Heights***

The early 2000s saw Miranda collaborating with [John Buffalo Mailer](/John_Buffalo_Mailer) and director [Thomas Kail](/Thomas_Kail) to refine *[In the Heights](/In_the_Heights)*. Playwright [Quiara Alegría Hudes](/Quiara_Alegr%C3%ADa_Hudes) joined the creative team in 2004, bringing her narrative expertise to the project. After its initial premiere in Connecticut in 2005 and a subsequent run off-Broadway at the 37 Arts Theater in 2007, *In the Heights* ascended to [Broadway](/Broadway_theatre), debuting in March 2008.

The musical garnered significant critical acclaim, receiving 13 [Tony Award](/Tony_Award) nominations and ultimately winning four, including the coveted [Best Musical](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Musical) and [Best Original Score](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Original_Score) awards. Its success was further cemented by a [Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album](/Grammy_Award_for_Best_Musical_Theater_Album). Miranda's portrayal of the lead character, Usnavi, earned him a nomination for the [Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Actor_in_a_Musical). He departed the Broadway production on February 15, 2009, but later reprised his role for the national tour's engagement in Los Angeles from June 23 to July 25, 2010, and again for the production's run in [San Juan, Puerto Rico](/San_Juan,_Puerto_Rico). He rejoined the cast for the final performances on Broadway, from December 25, 2010, until the show's closing on January 9, 2011, after a successful run of 1,185 regular performances.

During this period, Miranda also contributed to other theatrical ventures. He collaborated with composer [Stephen Sondheim](/Stephen_Sondheim) on Spanish-language translations for the 2009 Broadway revival of [West Side Story](/West_Side_Story). Additionally, he contributed two new songs to a revised version of the 1978 musical [Working](/Working_(musical)), which premiered at the [Asolo Repertory Theatre](/Asolo_Repertory_Theatre) in [Sarasota, Florida](/Sarasota,_Florida), in May 2008, following an invitation from composer-lyricist [Stephen Schwartz](/Stephen_Schwartz_(composer)).

Beyond his composing and acting work, Miranda engaged in various other pursuits. He worked as an English teacher at his former high school, contributed as a columnist and [restaurant critic](/Restaurant_critic) for the [Manhattan Times](/Manhattan_Times), and composed music for commercials. In 2003, he co-founded [Freestyle Love Supreme](/Freestyle_Love_Supreme), a hip hop improv group that achieved international recognition through tours at the [Edinburgh Festival Fringe](/Edinburgh_Festival_Fringe) and comedy festivals in [Aspen](/The_Comedy_Festival), [Melbourne](/Melbourne_International_Comedy_Festival), and [Montreal](/Just_for_Laughs). The group later developed a limited television series for Pivot in 2014 and made its Broadway debut in October 2019.

**2011–2014: *Bring It On* and Other Theatrical Work**

Miranda's collaboration with composer [Tom Kitt](/Tom_Kitt_(musician)) and lyricist [Amanda Green](/Amanda_Green) resulted in the musical [Bring It On](/Bring_It_On:_The_Musical), which premiered in Atlanta in January 2011. The musical embarked on a national tour before opening on Broadway at the [St. James Theatre](/St._James_Theatre) in August 2012, where it ran for a limited engagement. It garnered [Tony Award](/Tony_Awards) nominations for Best Musical and Best Choreography. In February 2012, Miranda performed in a staged concert of [Merrily We Roll Along](/Merrily_We_Roll_Along_(musical)) at [New York City Center](/New_York_City_Center) as part of the [Encores!](/Encores!) series.

In 2014, Miranda received an [Emmy Award](/Emmy_Award) for co-writing the song "Bigger!" with Tom Kitt for the opening number of the [67th Tony Awards](/67th_Tony_Awards). He also penned the music and lyrics for the one-act musical [21 Chump Street](/21_Chump_Street), performing as the narrator for its single performance at the [Brooklyn Academy of Music](/Brooklyn_Academy_of_Music) in June 2014, which was subsequently broadcast on [National Public Radio](/National_Public_Radio)'s [This American Life](/This_American_Life). Later that year, he starred in the Encores! revival of [Jonathan Larson](/Jonathan_Larson)'s [Tick, Tick... Boom!](/Tick,_Tick..._Boom!), under the artistic direction of [Jeanine Tesori](/Jeanine_Tesori).

**2011–2016: *Hamilton***

The genesis of Miranda's most celebrated work, [Hamilton](/Hamilton_(musical)), can be traced back to 2008 when he read [Ron Chernow](/Ron_Chernow)'s biography of [Alexander Hamilton](/Alexander_Hamilton). Inspired, he crafted a rap about Hamilton, which he performed at the White House in 2009. Miranda dedicated a significant amount of time to refining the song "[My Shot](/My_Shot)", aiming to capture Alexander Hamilton's intellectual depth. By 2012, he was presenting extended pieces based on Hamilton's life, collectively known as the "Hamilton Mixtape," which garnered significant attention, with *The New York Times* deeming it "an obvious game changer."

*[Hamilton](/Hamilton_(musical))* premiered off-Broadway at [The Public Theater](/The_Public_Theater) in January 2015, with Miranda not only writing the book and score but also starring as the titular character. The production was met with overwhelming critical acclaim and sold-out performances. In recognition of their collaborative efforts, Chernow and Miranda received the 2015 History Makers Award from the [New York Historical Society](/New_York_Historical_Society). The musical transferred to Broadway, beginning previews in July 2015 at the [Richard Rodgers Theatre](/Richard_Rodgers_Theatre) and officially opening on August 6, 2015, to universal praise. The immense demand for tickets led to the creation of [Ham4Ham](/Ham4Ham), a series of outdoor performances for lottery participants, hosted by Miranda and cast members for over a year.

Miranda's financial success from *Hamilton* was substantial, with reports indicating he earned $12.7 million in royalties by July 2017. The musical swept major awards, winning the [Tony Award for Best Musical](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Musical), and Miranda securing Tonys for [Best Original Score](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Original_Score) and [Best Book Of A Musical](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Book_of_a_Musical). He also earned a nomination for [Best Actor in a Musical](/Tony_Award_for_Best_Actor_in_a_Musical). The musical's unprecedented success was further recognized with a [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize_for_Drama) and a [Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album](/Grammy_Award_for_Best_Musical_Theater_Album). In May 2016, Miranda was honored with the [Drama League Award](/Drama_League_Award) [Distinguished Performance Award](/Drama_League_Distinguished_Performance_Award) for his portrayal of Alexander Hamilton.

Miranda's engagement with the White House extended beyond performances; in March 2016, he participated in a [freestyle rap](/Freestyle_rap) session with President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama). In April 2016, he co-authored *Hamilton: The Revolution* with Jeremy McCarter, a book chronicling the musical's creation and its cultural impact. Miranda performed his final show in *Hamilton* on July 9, 2016, but expressed his intent to return. He later announced a one-night reprisal of the role in January 2017 to honor President Obama's commutation of [Oscar López Rivera](/Oscar_L%C3%B3pez_Rivera)'s sentence. The documentary *Hamilton's America*, exploring the making of the musical, premiered in October 2016 and aired on [PBS](/PBS). A filmed version of the original Broadway production was released on [Disney+](/Disney%2B) in July 2020.

In January 2016, Miranda fulfilled a childhood dream by performing the offstage voice role of Loud Hailer in the Broadway production of [Les Misérables](/Les_Mis%C3%A9rables_(musical)), the first show he ever saw on Broadway.

**2019–present: Return to Theatre**

In January 2019, Miranda returned to the role of Alexander Hamilton for a limited three-week engagement of *Hamilton* at the [Luis A. Ferré Performing Arts Center](/Luis_A._Ferr%C3%A9_Performing_Arts_Center) in Puerto Rico. The highly anticipated run sold out within hours of tickets becoming available. Critics noted his "deeper on-stage emotions" and refined performance. In March of the same year, he portrayed [King Arthur](/King_Arthur) in a benefit concert of [Camelot](/Camelot_(musical)) at [Lincoln Center](/Lincoln_Center).

In 2023, Miranda contributed additional lyrics to the Broadway musical [New York, New York](/New_York,_New_York_(musical)). He is also reportedly working on a stage musical adaptation of the novel [The Warriors](/The_Warriors_(Yurick_novel)), with a concept album titled *[Warriors](/Warriors_(Lin-Manuel_Miranda_and_Eisa_Davis_album))*, created with [Eisa Davis](/Eisa_Davis), released in October 2024.

#### Film

**2012–2014: Early Work**

Miranda made his feature film debut in the [Walt Disney Pictures](/Walt_Disney_Pictures) live-action film [The Odd Life of Timothy Green](/The_Odd_Life_of_Timothy_Green) in 2012.

**2015–present: Disney Projects and Directorial Debut**

Miranda's association with [The Walt Disney Company](/The_Walt_Disney_Company) began in earnest in 2013 when he met with the studio. His submission of a six-song demo package to [Walt Disney Animation Studios](/Walt_Disney_Animation_Studios) initiated a fruitful collaboration:

*   **[Moana](/Moana_(2016_film))**: In 2014, Miranda was hired to write and perform music for Disney's 2016 animated feature, *Moana*. Collaborating with [Opetaia Foa'i](/Opetaia_Foa'i) and [Mark Mancina](/Mark_Mancina), he crafted the film's songs. He later reflected that the project served as an "ego check" amidst the burgeoning success of *Hamilton*. The film was a critical and commercial success, with Miranda's songwriting receiving particular praise. He performed "We Know the Way" and recorded a duet of "You're Welcome" for the film. His song "[How Far I'll Go](/How_Far_I%27ll_Go)" earned him a [Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media](/Grammy_Award_for_Best_Song_Written_for_Visual_Media) and nominations for a [Golden Globe](/Golden_Globe_Award), [Critics' Choice Award](/Critics%27_Choice_Movie_Awards), and [Oscar](/Academy_Awards).

*   **[Star Wars: The Force Awakens](/Star_Wars:_The_Force_Awakens)**: While working on *Hamilton*, Miranda contributed music to the 2015 film, composing a song for the cantina scene, paying homage to the iconic [Mos Eisley](/Mos_Eisley) Cantina sequence.

*   **DuckTales**: In May 2018, Miranda began voicing Fenton "Gizmoduck" Crackshell-Cabrera in the [Disney Channel](/Disney_Channel) reboot of [DuckTales](/DuckTales_(1987_TV_series)).

*   **[Mary Poppins Returns](/Mary_Poppins_Returns)**: Miranda starred as Jack, a lamplighter and former apprentice to Bert, in the 2018 sequel to the original *Mary Poppins*. This marked a significant role following his departure from *Hamilton*.

*   **[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker](/Star_Wars:_The_Rise_of_Skywalker)**: Miranda again contributed music to a Star Wars film, composing a song for a scene set on the desert planet Pasaana and making a cameo appearance in the 2019 film.

*   **[Hamilton](/Hamilton_(2020_film))**: The live-action filming of the original Broadway production, acquired by [Walt Disney Pictures](/Walt_Disney_Pictures), was released on [Disney+](/Disney%2B) in July 2020.

*   **[Encanto](/Encanto)**: Miranda reunited with Walt Disney Animation Studios for the 2021 animated musical *Encanto*. The film's soundtrack achieved remarkable success, with "[We Don't Talk About Bruno](/We_Don%27t_Talk_About_Bruno)" reaching number one on the US Billboard Hot 100. Miranda received an [Academy Award for Best Original Song](/Academy_Award_for_Best_Original_Song) nomination for "[Dos Oruguitas](/Dos_Oruguitas)".

*   **[The Little Mermaid](/The_Little_Mermaid_(2023_film))**: In August 2016, Miranda agreed to collaborate with [Alan Menken](/Alan_Menken) on new songs for Disney's live-action remake. He also served as a co-producer on the film, which was released in May 2023.

*   **[Mufasa: The Lion King](/Mufasa:_The_Lion_King)**: A longtime admirer of [The Lion King](/The_Lion_King), Miranda began composing songs for this prequel in early 2022, following a delay due to his commitments with other projects. The film is slated for release in December 2024.

The film adaptation of *[In the Heights](/In_the_Heights)* faced a protracted development process, with Universal Pictures initially planning a 2011 release before the project was canceled. The film eventually found a new home at [Warner Bros.](/Warner_Bros.) and was directed by [Jon M. Chu](/Jon_M._Chu). While Miranda originated the role of Usnavi on stage, he felt he was too old to play the character in the film, instead taking on the smaller role of the Piragua Guy. He expressed contentment in allowing [Anthony Ramos](/Anthony_Ramos_(actor)) and the new cast to create their own experience with the material. Miranda also served as a producer on the film, which was released in June 2021.

Miranda made his directorial debut with [Tick, Tick... Boom!](/Tick,_Tick..._Boom!_(film)), an adaptation of [Jonathan Larson](/Jonathan_Larson)'s musical, released on [Netflix](/Netflix) in 2021. He also starred as the titular character in, provided songs for, and served as executive producer of Sony Pictures Animation's *[Vivo](/Vivo_(film))*, released on Netflix in August 2021.

#### Television

**2007–2013: Early Roles**

Miranda's television career began with early appearances on shows like [The Sopranos](/The_Sopranos) (2007) and a recurring role as Juan "Alvie" Alvarez in [House](/House_(TV_series)) (2009–2010). He also contributed as a composer and actor to the 2009 revival of [The Electric Company](/The_Electric_Company_(2009_TV_series)) on [PBS Kids Go!](/PBS_Kids_Go!). He made guest appearances on [Modern Family](/Modern_Family) (2011) and had a recurring role in the NBC drama [Do No Harm](/Do_No_Harm_(TV_series)) (2013). His voice was also featured in an all-verse episode of [How I Met Your Mother](/How_I_Met_Your_Mother) in November 2013.

**2016–present: Comedy Roles and Other Projects**

Miranda's involvement in television expanded significantly in later years. He hosted [Saturday Night Live](/Saturday_Night_Live) in 2016, earning an [Emmy Award](/Emmy_Award) nomination for his performance. He also received two Emmy nominations for his guest appearances on [Curb Your Enthusiasm](/Curb_Your_Enthusiasm). In 2019, he took on the role of [Lee Scoresby](/Lee_Scoresby) in the [BBC](/BBC) television adaptation of [His Dark Materials](/His_Dark_Materials_(TV_series)).

He served as an executive producer for the FX limited series [Fosse/Verdon](/Fosse/Verdon) (2019), which garnered critical acclaim and an Emmy nomination for Outstanding Limited or Anthology Series. Miranda also voiced the character of Fenton Crackshell-Cabrera/Gizmoduck in the [Disney Channel](/Disney_Channel) reboot of [DuckTales](/DuckTales_(2017_TV_series)) from 2018 to 2020. In 2019, he was the guest narrator for [Disney's Candlelight Processional](/Disney%27s_Candlelight_Processional) at [Disneyland](/Disneyland). He performed the theme song for the [Netflix](/Netflix) series [The Magic School Bus Rides Again](/The_Magic_School_Bus_Rides_Again) and appeared as Lieutenant David Santiago in an episode of [Brooklyn Nine-Nine](/Brooklyn_Nine-Nine).

In 2019, Miranda partnered with producer [Norman Lear](/Norman_Lear) to create the documentary *[Rita Moreno: Just a Girl Who Decided to Go for It](/Rita_Moreno:_Just_a_Girl_Who_Decided_to_Go_for_It)*, which premiered at the [2021 Sundance Film Festival](/2021_Sundance_Film_Festival). He also collaborated on the song "Checks and Balances" for the 2021 Netflix animated series [We the People](/We_the_People_(2021_TV_series)). Miranda portrayed [Hermes](/Hermes) in the Disney+ series [Percy Jackson and the Olympians](/Percy_Jackson_and_the_Olympians_(TV_series)), which premiered in December 2023.

### Music

Miranda's musical contributions extend beyond his theatrical and film work. He is credited as a producer on "Peanuts 2 N Elephant" from Lil Wayne's album *[Tha Carter VI](/Tha_Carter_VI)*. He also provided backing vocals for several tracks on The Mountain Goats' 2025 album *[Through This Fire Across from Peter Balkan](/Through_This_Fire_Across_from_Peter_Balkan)*.

### Personal Life

#### Family

Lin-Manuel Miranda married Vanessa Nadal in 2010. The couple met in high school, and Nadal is an alumna of [Massachusetts Institute of Technology](/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology) (MIT) and [Fordham University School of Law](/Fordham_University_School_of_Law), where she practiced law. At their wedding reception, Miranda and the wedding party performed "[To Life](/To_Life_(song))" from [Fiddler on the Roof](/Fiddler_on_the_Roof). Nadal's Dominican and Austrian heritage contributed to Miranda's familiarity with the German language, which proved useful during the German translation of *Hamilton*.

The couple has two sons: Sebastian, born in 2014, and Francisco, born in 2018. Sebastian was named after the crab from *[The Little Mermaid](/The_Little_Mermaid_(1989_film))*, a film that inspired Miranda's involvement in the live-action remake. Miranda has stated that Sebastian is bilingual in English and Spanish and has some knowledge of German. Francisco is credited as a production baby in *Vivo*.

During a 2009 concert in San Juan, Puerto Rico, Miranda discovered his familial connection to artists [Residente](/Residente) and [iLe](/ILe) of [Calle 13](/Calle_13_(band)). Backstage, their mother revealed their shared ancestry tracing back to [Gilberto Concepción de Gracia](/Gilberto_Concepci%C3%B3n_de_Gracia), the founder of the [Puerto Rican Independence Party](/Puerto_Rican_Independence_Party). Miranda and Residente have since publicly confirmed their kinship. Miranda also performed on the opening track of Residente's debut album. Professional baseball player [José Miranda](/Jos%C3%A9_Miranda_(baseball)) is also a cousin.

#### Activism

Miranda has been a vocal advocate for [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico). Following a meeting with President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) in March 2016, Miranda joined U.S. Senators in advocating for congressional action to address Puerto Rico's substantial [government-debt burden](/Puerto_Rican_government-debt_crisis). He became particularly active in the aftermath of [Hurricane Maria](/Hurricane_Maria), with proceeds from his song "[Almost Like Praying](/Almost_Like_Praying)" contributing to the [Hispanic Federation](/Hispanic_Federation)'s $22 million raised for disaster relief efforts by December 2017.

Miranda directs proceeds from *Hamilton* to support [Graham Windham](/Graham_Windham), a nonprofit adoption agency founded by [Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton](/Elizabeth_Schuyler_Hamilton). He actively participates in their fundraising events and supports children in foster care. In March 2018, he performed "[Found/Tonight](/Found/Tonight)" with [Ben Platt](/Ben_Platt_(actor)) at the [March for Our Lives](/March_for_Our_Lives) rally in Washington, D.C.

To aid in Puerto Rico's reconstruction following hurricanes [Irma](/Hurricane_Irma) and [Maria](/Hurricane_Maria_(2017)), Miranda reprised his role as Usnavi in *Hamilton* in Puerto Rico in January 2018. The performances, which sold out rapidly, raised significant funds for the island's recovery. The production also contributed to improvements at the [Luis A. Ferré Performing Arts Center](/Luis_A._Ferr%C3%A9_Performing_Arts_Center).

In 2016, Miranda supported the passage of the [Puerto Rico Oversight, Management, and Economic Stability Act](/Puerto_Rico_Oversight,_Management,_and_Economic_Stability_Act) (PROMESA), intended to restructure Puerto Rico's debt. However, the subsequent austerity measures led to protests and criticism of Miranda, particularly when *Hamilton* was staged on the island. He later clarified his position, stating his opposition to the austerity measures and advocating for full debt relief.

### Awards and Honors

Miranda's extensive list of accolades includes a [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize), five [Grammy Awards](/Grammy_Award), three [Tony Awards](/Tony_Award), two [Primetime Emmy Awards](/Primetime_Emmy_Awards), and two [Olivier Awards](/Laurence_Olivier_Award), alongside nominations for two [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards). In 2015, he was recognized with a [Genius Grant](/Genius_Grant) from the [MacArthur Fellows Program](/MacArthur_Fellows_Program). *[Time](/Time_(magazine))* magazine named him one of the "Most Influential People in the World" in 2016, and he received a star on the Puerto Rico Walk of Fame. He was honored with a star on the [Hollywood Walk of Fame](/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame) in November 2018 and received the [Kennedy Center Honors](/Kennedy_Center_Honors) in December 2018 for his creation of *Hamilton*.

He received Smithsonian Magazine's American Ingenuity Award in the History category in 2015 and the Portrait of a Nation prize from the [Smithsonian National Portrait Gallery](/Smithsonian_National_Portrait_Gallery) in 2019. The album *[The Hamilton Mixtape](/The_Hamilton_Mixtape)*, featuring various artists performing songs inspired by *Hamilton*, reached number one on the Billboard 200.

#### Honorary Degrees

Miranda has received numerous honorary degrees, including from [Yeshiva University](/Yeshiva_University) (2009), his alma mater [Wesleyan University](/Wesleyan_University) (2015), the [University of Pennsylvania](/University_of_Pennsylvania) (2016), the [University of Puerto Rico](/University_of_Puerto_Rico) (2016), and the [Royal Academy of Music](/Royal_Academy_of_Music) in [London, England](/London,_England) (2022). He has also delivered commencement addresses at Wesleyan and the University of Pennsylvania.

